{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491596","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491596"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:55:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:55:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"996"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"996","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/996"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.47,0.05,0.37,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"996"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48311"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"996","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/996"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"996"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33234"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"7992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2780"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2886"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42193"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48311","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/48311"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old man presents to the emergency department with a two week history of flu-like symptoms (malaise, sore throat, fever). Over the last four days, he has noticed the development of a painful rash that started all over his trunk and has now spread to involve his upper limbs on face. He saw his GP for his flu-like symptoms earlier in the week and was prescribed amoxicillin, for a presumed upper respiratory tract infection. He is normally healthy, although occasionally takes meloxicam for back pain. On examination, he appears unwell and distressed. His blood pressure is 105/76 mmHg, pulse 95/min and respiratory rate 22/min. He has conjunctival injection and his lips are chapped and bleeding. There is an erythematous dusky rash covering most of his torso and arms, with areas of skin peeling and bullae formation. Nikolsky\u0027s sign is positive.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bullous pemphigoid","Toxic epidermal necrolysis","Erythema multiforme minor","Stevens-Johnson syndrome","Delayed anaphylaxis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer to this question is \u003Cstrong\u003Etoxic epidermal necrolysis\u003C/strong\u003E (TEN).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStevens-Johnson syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E (SJS) and TEN are both severe skin disorders that lie on a spectrum of severity. SJS and TEN are characterised by mucosal involvement, extensive skin necrosis and epidermal detachment. SJS is classified by \u0026lt;10% body surface area (BSA) involvement, SJS-TEN overlap syndrome 10-30% BSA and TEN \u0026gt;30% BSA. Usually precipitated by medications, both can be caused by antibiotics, anticonvulsants, allopurinol and NSAIDs commenced 1-2 weeks prior to presentation. Management should be focussed on stopping the culprit drug and providing supportive treatment eg. haemodynamic support, avoiding complications eg. sepsis. Mortality for these conditions is high (up to 10% for SJS and at least 30% for TEN).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has recently been commenced on amoxicillin, which can be associated with SJS/TEN as a rare side effect. He displays signs of being systemically unwell, as well as the characteristic rash of SJS/TEN, which is associated with areas of dusky necrotic skin with formation of subepidermal blisters. Mucosal involvement is also manifested by conjunctival injection and chapped/bleeding lips. Nikolsky\u0027s sign refers to detachment and peeling of seemingly intact epidermis from the underlying dermis when the skin is gently rubbed. As the area of body surface involved is \u0026gt;30%, TEN is a more appropriate answer than SJS.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBullous pemphigoid\u003C/strong\u003E is an incorrect answer option, as whilst blisters are observed in this condition, patients are generally systemically well and the associated rash is itchy, not painful and are erythematous without dusky discoloration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EErythema multiforme\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Eminor\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by targetoid lesions that most commonly involve the peripheries before any central involvement. Most of the time, patients will be fairly stable and will not feel systemically unwell. This patient\u0027s presentation is far more severe than what is typically seen with erythema multiforme minor, making this an incorrect answer option.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis would be a very unusual timeline for \u003Cstrong\u003Edelayed anaphyalxis\u003C/strong\u003E. Whilst the onset of symptoms can occur up to days after exposure to a trigger (e.g. antibiotic), the timeline over which symptoms develop is not generally protracted. In other words, this patient\u0027s rash and systemic upset has developed over a period of days, rather than minutes or hours (as is generally the case with anaphylaxis). In addition, the rash of anaphylaxis is typically urticarial, rather than desquamating.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Toxic epidermal necrolysis is an uncommon complication of medications, particularly some antibiotics."],"references":["Creamer D, Walsh S, Dziewulski P, Exton L, Lee H, Dart JK, et al. U.K. guidelines for the management of Stevens-Johnson syndrome/toxic epidermal necrolysis in adults 2016. British Journal of Dermatology (1951). 2016 Jun;174(6):1194\u2013227"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33234"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"996"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33234","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/33234"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-09T21:12:09+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-06T20:53:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"996"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48311"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4955","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4955"},"